((AISFJAOJHGUASJIGUHJGOWJIHBGWGJ
((SDKJSGKSG WASNT ME WHO MADE IT))
Driving up to the place and parking, Polaris got out of his car and locked it, rolling up his sleeves and stuffing them into his pocket as he scanned the area for Shale.
...He hoped nobody would ask for his number this time.
Shale walks in from a random street the opposite direction from her house, hands in her pockets and eyeing the car park
Picking up on Shale’s unique hair, he holds up his free arm.
Not like she’ll need him to, he’s the tallest person there for miles, but it’s still helpful.. probably.
"Oh! Hi!" Shale grins and waves back, walking over.
Polaris smiles at Shale, nodding. “Shale. How are you?” he asks, hoping that’s a good conversation starter.
...his ankle hurt.
"I'm doing okay. Okay as I can be." she jokes. "Is your ankle okay?" Shale is incredibly good at picking out injuries, which she doesn't like to admit, but it comes in useful, sometimes.

Externally, Polaris puts on a convincing confused ‘what do you mean?’ face, but internally he’s freaking out.. fuck, he’s not letting his own failure fuck up this night. “Yeah. I don’t know why you ask. Come on, I got us a table.”
"You're putting most of your weight on your other leg. Seriously, are you okay?" Shale tilts her head and raises her eyebrows. She most definitely has the feeling that Polaris is lying to her.
He releases the weight on his good leg, sharing the weight with both, no matter how painful it is. “I was probably just tired without realizing.. Is this better?”
"You can stand the way you were, I was just curious." Shale holds her hands up. "I'll stop talking about it if you want."
“Do what you want,” he sighs out. “Come on, they’ll give our table to someone else at this point,” Polaris points to the restaurant

"Okay." Shale has... somewhat enough sense not to push further. She'll try later. Right now... She doesn't know what Polaris needs but comfort normally works. Right. No making someone uncomfortable. That'll be... fun.
Once they’ve gotten in and gotten their table Polaris looks around. It’s decently packed...... fuck.
Crowds are not his strong suit. Nonetheless, he pushes down the boiling anxiety and glances towards a menu.
Shale sits back and watches the crowd, assessing threats and exit points. She takes a menu but barely pays attention to it, flipping her tail wildly.
Polaris eyes Shale from over the menu...
“Calm down.”
"I'm that obvious, huh?" Shale sighs and settles down. She wraps her tail around her chair leg and goes back to reading the menu, properly this time.

Polaris smiles a little behind the menu. Shale has calmed down, he’s not putting weight on his ankle, and he’s not really scanning the menu that well, since he already chose what he’d get... but he can at least zone out, not think about what happened not even an hour beforehand.

Shale relaxes- she's assessed all the threats, she's figured out how to make Polaris happy for now, she can be relatively at ease. Then having no anxiety gives her anxiety and she starts reassessing the situation
Polaris kicks her ankle with the foot on his good leg.
“Cut that shit out. We’re muns, we don’t hurt each other.”
"Okay! Okay." Shale offers a smile that's not as wide as her normal one, but she hopes its comforting, and forces herself to focus on the menu.
Polaris sighs, putting down his menu.
“Shale, put it down. They’re busy, they won’t get to us in a while, let’s talk.”
Shale nods and puts down the menu. "So.. what do you want to talk about?"
“..I heard you met Hermès and Foo Fighters muns,” he starts off with. That should get a conversation going.
Shale brightens up. "Yeah!! I'm so glad I found them.. I was really missing them when I returned to the void... They're good friends and partners."
Polaris puts on a smile. “I’m glad,” he states, not knowing how to continue. Honestly, he just hopes that Shale is like Malachite, and will ramble on about them.
"I know right?? They're wonderful. Did you always know your team in the human world were muns or did you go without them for a while like I did?"
Oh. He didn’t expect that.
He hums, looking down at his hands, which he had been fiddling with on the table.

“I lived on my own for the first million years of my life. Then, a couple hundred thousand years after that, after I went on my first mission, I met Malachite. And then Argenti, Seriya, and you guys.”
Shale's eyes widen. "For the first million years- Didn't you get lonely?!" *Thank god for Malachite, Polaris probably wouldn't have ever met anyone else if it weren't for him*, she muses to herself

Polaris shrugged. “Not really. I had... co-workers to talk to.” He almost forgot that those people were technically his ‘co-workers’. Fellow saviors... he doesn’t see them much anymore. Wonder if they retired, by now. They were all millions of years older than him, after all.
"But even then! No friends?" Shale tilts her head. How would someone even survive that long with nobody to talk to... she'd spent a hundred years alone once and it had been torture
He shrugged again. “Guess not. Those co-workers were kinda friends, but mostly they felt like parents. Even then, I only saw them for a few minutes each day. Not much to go off of.”
"That's... Wow. I kind of feel sorry for you now. That must have been hard." Shale taps her finger on the table sympathetically.
He raises an eyebrow at her, confused.
“Should it have been?”
(Shale, who has a mom, Dad, and two sisters: can’t relate)
"It should have been. But maybe you wouldn't realise that... We're very different in personality so maybe you *can* go without contact for a long time. I know that I can't."
“...Hm,” they hum, thoughtful.
“It was hard at first. It sucked. It felt like something was missing, but I didn’t know what. I got used to it eventually,” he shrugged one more time, resting his chin in his hand.
"You'd kind of have to get used to it, wouldn't you..." Shale mused, and pursed her lips, thinking. "I'm glad you met Malachite, though. I don't think you would have branched out on your own."
“I guess..” they mumble.
“I don’t feel too much different from before. I feel a bit lighter, but everything else is the same.”
"Lighter is good! You're a dark and somewhat hurt person, every bit counts." Shale says brightly
“Hurt?” Polaris asks, curious. *Care to emphasize?* they think. They meant to say that at loud, but the look that they’re giving Shale should probably be enough.

Shale winces - she's been impulsive again, she's not supposed to be impulsive - and shrugs. "Lots of times you come back from missions you... have this haunted look on your face, you're uncomfortable with lots of things, and I've noticed things that... I read that to be that you're hurting because of something."
“...Oh.” Polaris didn’t realize. “I thought I was used to it by now. Guess not. Didn’t think I was hurt, either..” Polaris looks at his hands, which he started fidgeting with on the table again.
*...Am I hurt?* he asks himself.
"I-I'm sorry- I'm being too blunt again." Shale smacks her foot with her tail under the table and shuts up.
Polaris shakes his head, slightly panicking, though trying not to show it. “You’re fine. It’s fine.”
Polaris looks at Shale, realizing she’s panicking, and sighs. “Shale, 100% of the time I’m more worried about what others think of me to care to what others *say* to me. Don’t freak out.”

"I guess we're similar in that respect then.." Shale says quietly, but calms down anyway. "Look, I studied how people work a lot when I'm in the human world and some of it comes back with me. I just tend to use my skills in that respect too much."

“...I’m surprised,” he remarks. Though, you wouldn’t see the surprise on his face. In fact, Polaris realized he hasn’t changed his expression since he got out of the car. He hopes that doesn’t scare Shale.

"Why's that?" Shale has indeed noted the fact that Polaris hardly ever changes facial expressions. She puts it down to a need to please others, or repressing feelings, or another few hypotheses she's come up with.
“You can remember your human experiences. That takes a lot of experience. How long have you been a Reaper?” he asks, curious.
"I've been a Reaper for a long time... About a million and a bit years, now. I started my job young." Shale smiles wryly
(**HOW LONG**)
Polaris’ expression doesn’t change at that, but inside he *does* frown...
((A VERY LONG TIME SDGJKHSDKGJ))
“..I didn’t know Plasma took in children for jobs.”

"I don't remember back that far." Shale smooths her face and keeps a blank expression. "All I've got is my sense of time. Could've been earlier, could've been later. I think that's the right number though. I did some digging."
“Do you... remember your age?” Polaris asks, their anger building up. They’ll have to talk to the higher ups about who they recruit.
"I'm about.... 1.6 million years old, I think." Shale shrugs again. "I don't mind, I've been doing it for a long time and it's not a bad job once you get past a few universes."
“Shale, that can’t be right,” Polaris stated.
“1.6 million... Is a million 600 thousand. That’s your age.”
"Yeah? I can do math." Shale worriedly wraps her tail around the chair, then the table, then her leg
“A-Ah, my bad... I meant, do you remember the age you started?”

"Oh! I misinterpreted, heh. I would've been... 500, 000 years old?" Shale bites her lip in case she's said something wrong and everything's going to go wrong now and she's going to ruin this relationship like she ruins universes.
“...You’re fucking kidding me,” is all Polaris responds with, their face not noticeably changing, again, but inside.... god, you don’t wanna see.
"Oh crap..." Shale knows it, she's done *something* wrong, but she doesn't know why and now Polaris definitely feels angry
Polaris burries his face in his hands. “Fuck. Plasma, you *fucker,*” is all he mumbles out.
He sighs, pushing his face further into his palms. “Godddddddd I can’t deal with thisssssssss.”
"I'm sorry!" blurts Shale, even though she doesn't know why she's apologizing but she *knows* she's done something wrong and its her fault
“What?” Polaris almost slams his hands down onto the table. “Kid, what are you apologizing for?”
"I make people angry without thinking, I'm sorry, it's my fault-" Shale goes paler
“Shale— shit, Shale, I’m sorry, I didn’t mean to make you think it’s your fault, I’m sorry,” he reaches over to gently take her hands in his.
Shale clutches at his hands unintentionally. "No... It's fine, that's just.. My normal reaction. You don't need to apologize."

He shakes his head. “No, I do. I caused you unnecessary worry, and I should have chosen my actions more carefully. What I did wasn’t ok, and I’m sorry. Want to talk about something else, now?” Polaris tries to calm Shale down. Maybe it’s the Jotaro in him, bringing out these father-instinct in him to comfort Shale, but he wants her to understand it’s not her fault.
"Y-Yeah...." Shale takes a deep breath and nods. It's... actually somewhat comforting, having Polaris talking to her. She doesn't know why, but an actual, true smile spreads on her face.
“Alright. Why not talk about your partners again? They seem really nice. You didn’t get much time to talk about them.”

"They are nice... Hermes, or Gemi, is usually the first person I meet in prison... She helps out with all kinds of tips and tricks, and she has an amazing amount of skills!" Shale takes another breath. "And Foo, or Unitas, we essentially save, and then *I* get to teach her everything I know that Hermes taught me!"
“Mhm?” he hums in a ‘is that so?’ sort of manner, trying to act as interested as possible, at least to keep Shale’s mind off of... whatever the hell happened before this.
"Yeah! It's like a cycle... They're really awesome. Then I meet Emporio and Hermes and I have never missed a timeline without saying we should adopt him, and Weather and Ana..."
“...Anasui,” he states with an eye roll.
"Yup. Foo ended up telling me about how creepy they get sometimes, I am *well* aware, now." Shale shrugs

“Thank the stars...” Polaris sighed. He always hated Anasui. The guy murdered his past girlfriend in cold blood, and then asked Jotaro if he could marry his daughter? That guy was fucked up in the head.

"If I do find a timeline where they aren't half as bad, I still might consider keeping them around though..." Shale had only recently found out how bad Anasui was, but several hundred timelines of dating someone tended to leave a mark
If Polaris had to be feeling anything right now, it would be the emotional equivalent of :mm:.
“.........If he had a mun version, I’d glock him,” is all Polaris said in response to that.
"Please don't glock him." Shale says with a tinge of amusement in her voice. "Your inner dad is showing, by the way." she teases.
He tries to hide it, but his eyes widen and his face goes bright purple. He shoves the lower part of his face in his hands. “....................I’m not.”
Shale tilts her head and laughs. "Suuuure."
“J-Just start talking about your partners again, you hopeless lesbian..” he mumbles.
"Okayyyyy!" Shale grins wickedly. "They're awesome... I really need to teach Foo how to use a phone one of these timelines.." She rambles on
Polaris listens— though, not really. They are listening, but they’re also dissociating. That last mission really left them..... disoriented, is a good word for it.
Then, the waiter comes to take their orders. I have never been to a mexican restaurant before so let’s just assume they ordered whatever the fuck looked good.
Shale just keeps rambling until she runs out of content to talk about (A rare occurrence, she hardly ever does that), and falls silent.
“You seem happy,” Polaris comments once they snap out of their dissociation, which takes a lot more willpower than they’d like.
"I guess I am, when I talk about topics I want to." Shale knows that's not quite the reason, she's just insanely good at distracting herself and changing moods.
“That’s nice. To be able to talk and be happy about it, I mean.” *Shit. That came out wrong.*
"Do you... not normally?" Shale pushes any other emotions away and pulls curiosity to the front
“Not normally what?” *Fuck.*
"Talk about your interests and stuff." *Don't look concerned, don't look concerned*
“No, not usually. I’d like to, but I don’t talk much.” He gestures to himself with his free hand as if to say ‘obviously’
Well, no, not to say ‘obviously’. But more like ‘I thought we knew this’
"Well then, we can start now! What are your interests? I'm all ears." Shale sits back
“...” Polaris looks at Shale, eyes widening ever so slightly. As if to say, “actually?”
"Go for it," Shale says softly, and sits forward again

“...Well, I enjoy processes,” Polaris starts. They have a rapid love for marine biology and astrology, yes, but more than anything, the process of something is what intrigues them the most. The process of how a black hole is made, the process of human development, the process of how ecosystems and species grow off and expand, that’s what intrigues them the most. Something about how things can come to be, their growth and expansion, it’s always been fascinating to them. So, they started off with something simple— something easy to memorize, especially since one of their friends is a fan of it.
“You know what animation is, right?”
"Of course! It looks awesome." Shale smiles

Polaris gives a soft smile. “Mhm. When I was living alone and wasn’t on missions, all I would do is watch human movies. TV shows, movies, commercials, as long as it was animated, I would watch it. Soon enough, during my first mission in the human world, I learned how it was made. And when I met Malachite, he explained it even further to me. It’s interesting.”

“First, a human will go in front of a camera and record the movements that the characters will make. Sometimes, they’ll strap a camera to their head and run in a controlled area to get a feel for what the character themself is seeing, so that they can animate that, as well. Once the recording is done, they download it into a software and begin to draw storyboards off of it. Those are sketches out panels, usually not animated, but sometimes they’ll add movement to them or lines to show where the characters will be moving in a scene. Next, they clean it up..” Polaris goes on about it, talking quietly, but still passionately.
Shale listens intently, pleased at seeing Polaris talking about their passions. And besides, this was actually interesting- She'd always never been able to see how animation worked, really
((WOULD YOU LIKE ME TO CONTINUE
((YES PLEASE))
((*YESSSSSSSSS*
// :blurryeyes:

“If they’re going for frame-by-frame animation, they do official sketches for frames that show main actions, before going back in and adding in ‘inbetween’ frames, or frames that show the actual process of the action,” they held out their hand, moving it back and forth quickly. “In animation, they’d probably first draw the frames of my hand in the beginning,” he moves his hand to one point, “and the end,” then he moves it to a different point. “Afterwards, when all the main frames like that are done, they’ll animate the blur inbetween then.”

“After they’re done with the sketches, if they’re animating in 2D, they go in and do the most tantalizing part, the lineart. They draw clean lines over all of the sketches they’ve done, and afterwards, they go in and add in base colors, or the main colors to a character. For example, if we were being animated and in the process of having our base colors added, all your hair would look like is a flat black and green, and my skin would just be a flat gray color. No shading, no lighting, nothing.”

“After they’re done with the base colors, they add lines to show where the shading and lighting would be. Once that’s done, they actually fill in the lines with the shading, and then they remove the guide lines they used before. Now, the characters are officially animated and colored.”

“After that, they create the backgrounds and implement them into each scene. Most of the time, a background doesn’t change, though usually little details will be animated, like leaves blowing in the wind, or a candle flame flickering. Other than that, since nothing much in a room usually moves, there’s not much more work to be added to it.

“Once the backgrounds added in, they add more lighting and filters to the scene to create a general mood. For example, if there were light streaming in from a window nearby, they would add the lighting to the room and characters to show that, and add a filter to it to create a general mood, usually dramatic, and make things more interesting.”

“But if you’re animating in 3D, it’s a completely different story. After the storyboards are done, you don’t go in to do the sketching like you would with 2D. Instead, you take the 3D base for the characters and implement them into the storyboarded scene, programming the characters to move a specific way. The way they look before you add in the details of how their limbs and other things are supposed to move became a meme in the human world not too long ago...”
((**you know what i’m talking about dont fucking lie to me**
((Yes I do and this is the best thing))

“Either way, once that’s done, the animators will go in and change how the characters limbs move. For example, before all this, a 3D model moving from one side of the room to another would look like this,” he puts his pointer and middle finger on the table, keeping his fingers still as he moves his hand from one side of the table to another. “But once they’ve gone in and made the limbs move, it looks like this,” he puts his hand back, but this time, makes the fingers move like regular legs would.

“But that doesn’t mean that it’s finished. Once that’s done, the animators will add in the background, locate a light source and add in lighting and shading into there. Usually, at this point, a completely different department or single person is arranged to take care of the lighting and shading. The difference is incredible, at that point.”

“Then, once the general animation is done, that’s when they’ll send it to the sound department to add in sound effects, like crashing or shattering. Once that’s done, if necessary, voice actors will go in and speak so that their words sync up with the lip movements of the characters. After that, music is added, and boom. You have an animation.”

((oki))
Shale hmmed. "That's actually pretty interesting!"
Polaris snapped out of his thoughts when he heard that, and he wanted to respond, but he was just kinda... dazed. He was looking forward blankly.
"I mean, the whole process seems so full of talent and work and.. Hello?" Shale notices Polaris's face and waves

Polaris was so confused. What just happened? He never spouted out his interests before. In fact, he didn’t even realized he *knew that much* about it until he rambled about it for what seemed like hours. The food’s already here. When did the food get here? What the fuck was this feeling???

Shale smiles. "A little dazed?" she asks. She doesn't know the feeling herself, but she definitely knew what the psychological effect of talking about your interests for the first time in a long while was
“...........I have never talked about myself in my entire life.”
Shale would have spat out whatever she was eating/drinking, but she wasn't, so she just looked shocked. "I'm sorry, what?"
Polaris put his hands to the side of his head. His eyes were wide and dazed. His mouth was— was he smiling, frowning, both? He didn’t know. What the fuck.

“I have never talked about myself in my life. I have never talked that *much* in my life. I have never talked that *long* in my life. I’m going to puke. I need a second,” he pushed his chair out, standing up and rushing to the nearest restroom.

Shale sits there and processes what happened. "Oh." She's... maybe done something wrong but there's also the fact that. Wow. This is... vaguely confusing. If they don't come back sometime soon... Shale will probably text them
.....cue very loud vomiting. Hopefully the restaurant can’t hear, but it’s still loud.
Shale fidgets nervously, and starts to spin her plait in a circle, like she does when she's nervous.
....he comes back after a bit and casually sits down, beginning to eat his food as if nothing happened.
"Alright?" Shale is eating kind of slowly, as if in thought. Which she is, but she's not trying to show it
“...I think that... maybe my childhood wasn’t good.”
Polaris couldn’t put those words out any other way. They really couldn’t think of a more or less complex way to word it— they just... think that their childhood might not have been a good one.
*What gives you that idea?* Shale thinks, but tactfully doesn't say it. "Perhaps. It does seem so."

“...I. I feel like it might not have been good, and... I don’t know why,” they continue on, still dazed. “I don’t remember it being bad. I was lonely, and it hurt, but it never felt... like it was *bad*, perse. I just assumed everyone went through it.”
“S-So, this is a weird thing to ask, but. Uh, Shale..” he looked down, almost ashamed. “Can you, uh.. tell me what was wrong with my past? At least, what you think seems wrong about it?”
*I can’t.. seem to find a reason to dislike it, please find it for me,* is all that he can think.

"Hey. That's okay. Most people don't think that their childhood was that bad, and that's what's.. well, bad about it." Shale thinks for a few seconds. "As for an analysis. You never had anyone. To socialize with, to make friends with, to even have a proper parental figure in your life. You had nobody to look up to or admire, or nobody to look up to or admire you. That's enough to make anybody lost. The fact that you've *never* told anyone about your interests, or yourself, makes me think that you never felt comfortable enough to open up like that to anyone in your childhood. You didn't feel safe, or you never had a strong enough connection with anyone, or both."

"Then you got tossed out into a job that doesn't really help people's mental health, and by then your beliefs were set in a harsher world than the rest of us. A world where there was nobody to care for you, or be your friend." Shale takes a breath. "You've been alone, Polaris. You've been alone for much too long. But now, look here! You've got people who care about you and want to learn about your interests, and about you."
((holy crap that was a paragraph))
Polaris looked at Shale, still dazed, and.. well, he almost cried. You could see his eyes were getting watery, but he refused to cry. Especially out in public.

He looked down into his plate of food, just... casually thinking.
*...They care about me* was what he was thinking. It was the sort of thing that he did *know,* but it never really... settled in until now.
“...You guys care about me,” he said out loud, quiet, but not quiet enough to be a whisper. It was as if a toddler had just learned a new word, and was saying it correctly for the first time.
“And...” Polaris looked back up at Shale, their pokerface breaking ever so slightly. “I care about you guys.”
"We do." Shale says encouragingly. She smiles at Polaris, and her smile grows wider at seeing expression. "That's it.." she says quietly. "I'm proud."
Polaris looked at his plate, and saw small tears plop onto the edge of it. He was crying.
Oh god, *he was crying.*
Pushing his chair out and standing up again, Polaris rubbed his eyes lightly. “Let’s go.”
Shale nods and stands up. "It's okay to cry, you know? Lots of people don't see it that way but there is nothing wrong with expressing how you feel, no matter what you've been led to believe."

“...Sure,” is all Polaris responded with. Taking out some money and casually leaving it on the table (he probably left too much but who cares, he had way too much on him anyways. The workers can have a field day). “Do you want to go anywhere before we head home?”
"Nowhere in particular! Do you?" Shale asks
“Not really, that’s why I asked you.”
"Fair enough. I guess we can just head home." Shale doesn't press anything, but still tilts her head curiously
Polaris nods in understanding, walking out of the restaurant after nodding to some of the waiters and waitresses.

Honestly it’s a miracle nobody came up to talk to him. Deadass, the reason Jotaro always has girls surrounding him (and why it annoys him so fucking bad) is because Polaris has to deal with the same bullshit. But right now he’s feeling emotionally constipated, and he needs to go home, have a mental breakdown, and sleep for a couple hundred thousand years.
Getting to the parking lot, he turned to Shale. “I’ll drive you home.”
"Oh! Thank you." Shale doesn't reject the proposal, but she's surprised nonetheless. She doesn't know why.

Lamia is here
Venor follows. "Window seat?" She asks.
"Yes."
"Fair enough. It's the most strategic, considering the table nearest to the door is taken." She points out, and heads over.
Lamia sat down. "Ever since Jonathan and Dio were kids, they shared a birthday."
"Really? Why's that?" Venor rests her elbows on the table and interlaces her fingers.
"Because...they were born on the same day."
"Oh. Curious that it worked out like that." Venor purses her lips in thought. "That being said, one of my companions, Deth, was born on the same day as Bella Kishibe, but a few years before."
"I see." Lamia turned to the waiter and ordered some iced tea
Venor didn't order anything. She wasn't particularly fond of drinking anything. "I never said this before... My apologies. Happy Birthday, Lamia."
"Thank you." he nods
"Least I could do. Or say. Do you normally celebrate your birthday?"
"Solus is usually the center of attention...I can see why. I would never tell him, but I respect the man."
"So you'd feel... lonely? On your birthday?" Venor guesses. "And I won't tell him."
"Usually. I used to have a legion of followers, but I have yet to meet any of their muns...aside from Midler."
"Followers... But what about friends? Surely you must have some friendship towards someone..." *Hypocrite*. Venor didn't care.
//shit I forgot about Lamia
"The closest friend Dio had was a man by the name of Enrico Pucci."
((lmao you good))
"I see... Shale's mentioned him once or twice. What was he like?"
"A very...curious boy. Let me stay in his church one night without questioning it."
"Let *Dio*? In a *church*?" Venor snorts.
"Yup. I've read stories where vampires are fended off by anything holy. RIP to them but I'm different."

"Your vampirism is like nothing I've seen before... Sucking blood through your fingers - But you still have fangs. Defeated by the sun, but not holy objects. I could go on.... But I find it very interesting. Bella Kishibe only meets one vampire through her lifetime, but that encounter is quickly dealt with."
"Another weakness vampires have in literature that I don't is garlic."
"Very interesting. I wonder where all that literary myth comes from, then."
"Vampires in literature are such pussies. Killed by RUNNING WATER? Can't be let in a house if you don't invite them?!"

Venor nods in agreement. "I always thought their restrictions were harsh, and politeness has no place when you're about to attack and kill someone." Venor pauses. "Except if you're taunting your enemy, then you can be mock polite."
"Taunting is a favorite pastime of mine."
"Same here! It's a habit I carry over." Venor smiles slightly.
"How delightful."

"I've used it against most of the people I've fought - There was only one I didn't and that's because they punched me in the mouth." Venor looks quite pleased with herself for someone with no emotions.
"It's definitely a favorite. One time I used my time stop to move someone down stairs."
"If that's not a flex, I don't know what is. Who was it?" Venor is grinning unintentionally
"Polnareff."
Venor grins, truly, and she doesn't know why. "That's absolutely amazing. I love your style."
"Why thanks. When was the last time YOU used taunting?"

"Oh, last timeline. I kept shoving my enemy down, and told them 'You seem to keep falling! Let me help you up', and then grabbing their hand and swinging them into a wall. It was fun." Venor's eyes gleam.
Lamia laughs. "Nice."
